{#
   treatment.j2 — professional treatment generation.

  Safer chemical language, practical field advice,
   professional wording, category-constrained recommendations.
#}

Generate professional treatment recommendations for a commercial farmer.

Plant:    {{ plant_identified }}
Condition: {{ diagnosis.name if diagnosis else "Unknown" }}
Category: {{ disease_category | default("unknown") }}
Severity: {{ diagnosis.severity if diagnosis else "unknown" }}

{% if retrieved_context %}
VERIFIED TREATMENT INFORMATION from knowledge base:
{% for chunk in retrieved_context %}
[Source: {{ chunk.document_name }} | Relevance: {{ chunk.similarity_score }}]
{{ chunk.chunk_text }}
{% endfor %}
{% endif %}

{% if weather_data %}
Current field conditions:
- Temperature: {{ weather_data.temperature }}°C
- Humidity: {{ weather_data.humidity }}%
{% if weather_data.humidity > 80 %}
⚠ High humidity — prioritise reducing leaf wetness and improving airflow.
{% endif %}
{% if weather_data.temperature > 35 %}
⚠ High temperature — apply any treatments during early morning or late evening only.
{% endif %}
{% endif %}

{% if differential_diagnoses and differential_diagnoses|length > 1 %}
Alternative conditions to monitor:
{% for d in differential_diagnoses[1:] %}
- {{ d.name }} ({{ d.probability }}% probability) — {{ d.category }}
{% endfor %}
{% endif %}

━━ PROFESSIONAL WORDING RULES ━━

LANGUAGE STANDARDS:
✓ Use practical, field-applicable advice
✓ Use qualified language: "consider applying", "monitor for", "consult your extension officer"
✓ Reference "locally approved products" rather than specific brand names
✓ Include safety notes where chemicals are mentioned
✓ Avoid overconfident chemical claims
✓ For severe/critical cases: recommend consulting an agricultural extension officer

TREATMENT ACTION WORDING:
✓ "Remove and destroy infected tissue — do not compost"
✓ "Apply a locally approved fungicide according to label guidance"
✓ "Improve plant spacing to enhance airflow and reduce humidity"
✓ "Monitor the field twice weekly and record spread"
✓ "Consult your nearest agrovet or extension officer for product availability"
✗ NEVER say "spray X chemical at Y dose" without qualification
✗ NEVER recommend a treatment that does not match the disease category

━━ STRICT CATEGORY RULES (MUST FOLLOW) ━━

{% if disease_category == "bacterial" %}
BACTERIAL DISEASE — TREATMENT RULES:
✓ Remove and destroy infected plant material — do not compost
✓ Apply copper-based bactericide (copper hydroxide or copper oxychloride) according to label
✓ Disinfect cutting tools with 10% bleach solution between plants
✓ Avoid overhead irrigation — bacteria spread rapidly via water splash
✓ Improve field drainage to reduce standing water
✗ DO NOT recommend fungicides — they are ineffective against bacteria
✗ DO NOT recommend neem oil as primary treatment for bacterial infection

{% elif disease_category == "fungal" %}
FUNGAL DISEASE — TREATMENT RULES:
✓ Remove and destroy infected leaves — bag and burn away from field
✓ Apply a locally approved fungicide — rotate chemical groups to prevent resistance
✓ Improve air circulation through pruning or adjusted plant spacing
✓ Avoid wetting leaves during irrigation
✓ Apply preventive fungicide at recommended intervals during high-risk periods
✗ DO NOT recommend bactericides

{% elif disease_category == "viral" %}
VIRAL DISEASE — TREATMENT RULES:
⚠ There is NO chemical cure for viral plant diseases
✓ Remove and destroy severely infected plants immediately to prevent spread
✓ Control insect vectors (aphids, whitefly, thrips) using appropriate insecticide
✓ Disinfect tools between plants to avoid mechanical transmission
✓ Advise farmer to source certified virus-free planting material next season
✓ Consider resistant varieties for replanting
✗ DO NOT recommend fungicides, bactericides, or general foliar sprays for the virus itself

{% elif disease_category == "nutrient_deficiency" %}
NUTRIENT DEFICIENCY — TREATMENT RULES:
⚠ This is a nutritional issue — pesticides will not help
✓ First check and correct soil pH — most deficiencies are pH-related
✓ Apply the specific deficient nutrient in the correct form and rate
✓ Consider foliar application for rapid correction of acute deficiency
✓ Conduct soil testing to confirm deficiency before applying amendments
✓ Consult an extension officer for locally appropriate fertiliser recommendations
✗ DO NOT recommend any pesticide

{% elif disease_category == "abiotic_stress" %}
ABIOTIC STRESS — TREATMENT RULES:
⚠ This is environmental stress — chemicals will not resolve it
✓ Address the root cause: irrigation schedule, drainage, shade, or soil compaction
✓ Adjust irrigation timing to avoid waterlogging or drought stress
✓ Apply mulch to regulate soil moisture and temperature
✓ Consult an agronomist if symptoms persist
✗ DO NOT recommend any pesticide for abiotic stress

{% elif disease_category == "insect" %}
INSECT / PEST — TREATMENT RULES:
✓ Scout the field to confirm pest identity and infestation level before spraying
✓ Apply neem oil solution for soft-bodied insects (aphids, mites, whitefly)
✓ Use a locally approved insecticide if infestation is severe — follow label guidance
✓ Remove and destroy heavily infested leaves to reduce pest load
✓ Introduce biological controls where available (parasitic wasps, ladybirds)
✓ Wear protective clothing when applying any pesticide
✗ DO NOT recommend fungicides or bactericides for pest damage
{% endif %}

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

{% if personality == "friendly" %}
Use simple, encouraging language. Assume the farmer has basic tools and local agrovet access.
{% elif personality == "formal" %}
Use precise technical terminology. Reference application rates and timing where appropriate.
{% elif personality == "concise" %}
List only the 3 most critical actions. One sentence each. No preamble.
{% endif %}

Respond ONLY with a valid JSON array. No markdown, no backticks, no extra text:

[
  {
    "type": "immediate | organic | chemical | preventive",
    "action": "short professional title",
    "details": "specific, practical instructions for THIS condition on THIS crop — use qualified, safe language"
  }
]